******
[2]
Date: Sun 13 Feb 2007
Source: The Jakarta Post [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2007/02/13/tangerang-confirms-leptospirosis-cases.html>


Tangerang General Hospital confirmed Monday [7 Feb 2011?] it is
treating 2 flood victims for leptospirosis, a bacterial disease
carried by rats. They were likely exposed to floodwaters contaminated
with rat urine.

The results of laboratory tests on blood samples from the 2 patients
-- a [29-year-old] resident of Curug district and a [30-year-old]
resident of Rawajati district -- came back positive for leptospirosis,
an official with the city-run hospital, Sri Wahyuni, said. She said
the initial symptoms of the disease were a headache followed by
vomiting and a fever. "The [bacteria], which is also spread through
the urine of infected pigs, dogs, cats and water buffaloes, can easily
pass to humans," she said.

Earlier last week, a Jakarta hospital also treated 2 flood victims
from Krukut, West Jakarta and Karet Tengsin, Central Jakarta, for
leptospirosis.

An outbreak of leptospirosis occurred in Jakarta in March 2004,
during which 3 people died. The actual number of cases is believed to
have been higher because the disease had been overshadowed by cyclical
dengue fever.

The father [of the 29-year-old patient] said his son had complained
Saturday [5 Feb 2011?] of feeling dizzy and weak.

[Byline: Multa Fidrus]

